nce >= 0.9\n\nOutput your evaluation as JSON matching the NetworkEvaluation schema.\n", "user_message": "Evaluate this synthesis network:\n\nTARGET MOLECULE: Arginine\nOVERALL STRATEGY: This network is literature-constrained and therefore emphasizes that prebiotic arginine is weakly supported experimentally. The graph is built around the best-supported positive-but-underconstrained route, ornithine + cyanamide -> arginine in mild surface aqueous settings, while also embedding the dominant negative evidence that hydrothermal systems, spark discharge systems, ice photochemistry, meteoritic inventories, and mixed-valence iron mineral systems do not detect arginine or instead degrade it. Biochemical analog steps through citrulline and argininosuccinate are included only as mechanistic scaffolds because the provided literature explicitly retains them as pathway analogs rather than demonstrated prebiotic syntheses. Ten distinct pathways to the target are represented as alternative route narratives through the same connected bipartite graph, with convergence centered on ornithine, citrulline, argininosuccinate, cyanamide, and arginine.\n\nMOLECULES (17 nodes):\n  - mol_001: CO2 (carbon dioxide) [starting]\n  - mol_002: H2 (hydrogen) [starting]\n  - mol_003: CH2O2 (formate/formic acid) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_004: CH2O (formaldehyde) [intermediate]\n  - mol_005: C2H4O2 (glycolaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_006: C3H6O3 (glyceraldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_007: CHN (HCN) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_008: NH3 (ammonia) [starting]\n  - mol_009: CH2N2 (cyanamide) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_010: C5H12N2O2 (ornithine) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_011: CH3N3O5P (carbamoyl phosphate) [intermediate]\n  - mol_012: C6H13N3O3 (citrulline) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_013: C4H7NO4 (aspartate) [intermediate]\n  - mol_014: C10H18N4O6 (argininosuccinate) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_015: C6H14N4O2 (arginine) [target]\n  - mol_016: C4H4O4 (fumarate) [intermediate]\n  - mol_017: H2O (water) [starting]\n\nREACTIONS (12 nodes):\n  - rxn_001: mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_003 (Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_002: mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_004 (Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type formaldehyde generation) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_003: mol_004 -> mol_005 (Surface formose entry to glycolaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_004: mol_004, mol_005 -> mol_006 (Surface aldol extension to glyceraldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_005: mol_004, mol_008 -> mol_007 (UV-mineral generation of hydrogen cyanide) [Surface]\n  - rxn_006: mol_007 -> mol_009 (Surface concentration of HCN to cyanamide) [Surface]\n  - rxn_007: mol_009 -> mol_011 (Surface dry-state phosphorylation to carbamoyl phosphate analog) [Surface]\n  - rxn_008: mol_010, mol_011 -> mol_012 (Biochemical analog transcarbamylation of ornithine to citrulline) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_009: mol_012, mol_013 -> mol_014 (Biochemical analog condensation of citrulline with aspartate to argininosuccinate) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_010: mol_014 -> mol_015, mol_016 (Biochemical analog cleavage of argininosuccinate to arginine and fumarate) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_011: mol_010, mol_009 -> mol_015 (Surface cyanamide guanidinylation of ornithine to arginine) [Surface]\n  - rxn_012: mol_015, mol_017 -> mol_010 (Hydrothermal destruction of arginine to ornithine) [Hydrothermal]\n\nPATHWAYS (10):\n  - P1: Direct surface guanidinylation pathway (4 steps)\n  - P2: Hydrothermal-to-surface direct route via formose-fed cyanamide chemistry (7 steps)\n  - P3: Biochemical analog route through citrulline and argininosuccinate (4 steps)\n  - P4: Cyanamide-assisted entry into the biochemical analog sequence (5 steps)\n  - P5: Hydrothermal formaldehyde to biochemical analog route (7 steps)\n  - P6: Arginine recycling loop via hydrothermal destruction and surface resynthesis (2 steps)\n  - P7: Hydrothermal destruction followed by biochemical analog resynthesis (4 steps)\n  - P8: Sugar-mediated cyanide convergence to direct arginine route (5 steps)\n  - P9: Dual-convergence pathway through cyanamide and carbamoyl phosphate analog (6 steps)\n  - P10: Full cross-environment integrated pathway (9 steps)\n\nHUB MOLECULES: mol_009, mol_010, mol_012, mol_014, mol_015\nCONVERGENCE POINTS: 3\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH ON TARGET MOLECULE ===\nThe following research was conducted on the target molecule before network generation. Use it to assess whether the network aligns with known prebiotic chemistry literature.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n# Prebiotic synthesis report for arginine\n\n## 1. Executive summary\nUsing only the existing s6 consolidated bundle as the best-available validated basis, the evidence base for prebiotic arginine is dominated not by productive synthesis with quantified yield, but by **absence/non-detection**, **underconstrained plausibility**, and **destruction under hydrothermal conditions**. The s6 summary reports **10 total retained routes**, of which **0 are yield-backed**, **5 are non-yield routes**, and **5 are explicit arginine-not-detected routes** (`arginine_s6_summary.json`). No route in the retained bundle carries a numeric arginine yield with citation and exact locator; this is an explicit gap in the upstream analysis (`arginine_s6_summary.json`; `arginine_s6_final_submission.md`).\n\nThe strongest positive-but-underconstrained route retained is **ornithine + cyanamide -> arginine** (`ARG_R1`), cited to Longo et al. 2020 (*PNAS*) as contextual support, but the route is explicitly marked as inferred and as having **\"yield not reported\"** because no exact primary table/figure/page could be inspected in the recovered source context (`arginine_master_route_table.csv`). A second strong network edge is not synthetic but degradative: **arginine + hot water -> ornithine (+ additional products)** under hydrothermal conditions (`ARG_R2`), indicating that hydrothermal settings may act more as arginine sinks than sources in the retained bundle (`arginine_master_route_table.csv`).\n\nThe bundle also preserves repeated negative evidence: arginine is **not detected** in canonical Miller-Urey spark discharge (`ARG_R3`), H2S-rich Miller archive discharge (`ARG_R4`), interstellar/cometary ice UV photolysis (`ARG_R5`), meteoritic inventories (`ARG_R6`), and mixed-valence iron oxyhydroxide hydrothermal/mineral-gradient systems (`ARG_R10`) (`arginine_master_route_table.csv`). This repeated absence is therefore a central result, not a side note.\n\nOverall conclusion from the retained s6 evidence: arginine is chemically conceivable in prebiotic networks involving ornithine/cyanamide or biochemical analogs through citrulline/argininosuccinate, but **the best-supported observations in this bundle are non-detection and degradation rather than demonstrated abiotic accumulation of free arginine**.\n\n## 2. Ranked route table\nYield-backed routes are required to appear first. In the retained s6 bundle, **none exist**: `yield_backed_route_count = 0` (`arginine_s6_summary.json`). Therefore the ranked table begins with all retained non-yield routes, followed by all explicit not-detected routes. No routes are dropped.\n\n| Rank group | Route ID | Flag | Route | Precursors | Route type | T | P | pH | Catalyst / agents | Phase / medium | Environment | Yield | Citation | Exact locator |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Non-yield | ARG_R1 | NON_YIELD_ROUTE | ornithine + cyanamide -> arginine | ornithine; cyanamide | cyanamide / guanidinylation | low-to-moderate (not numerically constrained in recovered source context) | near-surface / ambient inferred; no direct pressure constraint recovered | not established | cyanamide | aqueous / concentrating aqueous | evaporative pond, wet-dry shoreline, or other mild aqueous setting | yield not reported (source: PMID:32561643; locations checked: full text via analyze_paper attempt only; SI not accessible in this run) | Longo et al., 2020, *PNAS* | access failure: analyze_paper