ydrothermal destruction feeding biochemical analog scaffold (4 steps)\n  - P5: Canonical spark-discharge to cyanide-linked network then direct arginine hypothesis (2 steps)\n  - P6: Sulfur-rich spark-discharge to cyanide-linked network then direct arginine hypothesis (2 steps)\n  - P7: Ice photolysis branch into connected nitrile chemistry then direct arginine hypothesis (2 steps)\n  - P8: Meteoritic branch into connected small-organic pool then direct arginine hypothesis (2 steps)\n  - P9: Iron oxyhydroxide hydrothermal negative branch then biochemical analog reconstruction (4 steps)\n  - P10: Dual-convergence route through ornithine hub (5 steps)\n\nHUB MOLECULES: mol_001, mol_002, mol_006, mol_008, mol_003\nCONVERGENCE POINTS: 5\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH ON TARGET MOLECULE ===\nThe following research was conducted on the target molecule before network generation. Use it to assess whether the network aligns with known prebiotic chemistry literature.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n# Prebiotic synthesis report for arginine\n\n## 1. Executive summary\nUsing only the existing s6 consolidated bundle as the best-available validated basis, the evidence base for prebiotic arginine is dominated not by productive synthesis with quantified yield, but by **absence/non-detection**, **underconstrained plausibility**, and **destruction under hydrothermal conditions**. The s6 summary reports **10 total retained routes**, of which **0 are yield-backed**, **5 are non-yield routes**, and **5 are explicit arginine-not-detected routes** (`arginine_s6_summary.json`). No route in the retained bundle carries a numeric arginine yield with citation and exact locator; this is an explicit gap in the upstream analysis (`arginine_s6_summary.json`; `arginine_s6_final_submission.md`).\n\nThe strongest positive-but-underconstrained route retained is **ornithine + cyanamide -> arginine** (`ARG_R1`), cited to Longo et al. 2020 (*PNAS*) as contextual support, but the route is explicitly marked as inferred and as having **\"yield not reported\"** because no exact primary table/figure/page could be inspected in the recovered source context (`arginine_master_route_table.csv`). A second strong network edge is not synthetic but degradative: **arginine + hot water -> ornithine (+ additional products)** under hydrothermal conditions (`ARG_R2`), indicating that hydrothermal settings may act more as arginine sinks than sources in the retained bundle (`arginine_master_route_table.csv`).\n\nThe bundle also preserves repeated negative evidence: arginine is **not detected** in canonical Miller-Urey spark discharge (`ARG_R3`), H2S-rich Miller archive discharge (`ARG_R4`), interstellar/cometary ice UV photolysis (`ARG_R5`), meteoritic inventories (`ARG_R6`), and mixed-valence iron oxyhydroxide hydrothermal/mineral-gradient systems (`ARG_R10`) (`arginine_master_route_table.csv`). This repeated absence is therefore a central result, not a side note.\n\nOverall conclusion from the retained s6 evidence: arginine is chemically conceivable in prebiotic networks involving ornithine/cyanamide or biochemical analogs through citrulline/argininosuccinate, but **the best-supported observations in this bundle are non-detection and degradation rather than demonstrated abiotic accumulation of free arginine**.\n\n## 2. Ranked route table\nYield-backed routes are required to appear first. In the retained s6 bundle, **none exist**: `yield_backed_route_count = 0` (`arginine_s6_summary.json`). Therefore the ranked table begins with all retained non-yield routes, followed by all explicit not-detected routes. No routes are dropped.\n\n| Rank group | Route ID | Flag | Route | Precursors | Route type | T | P | pH | Catalyst / agents | Phase / medium | Environment | Yield | Citation | Exact locator |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Non-yield | ARG_R1 | NON_YIELD_ROUTE | ornithine + cyanamide -> arginine | ornithine; cyanamide | cyanamide / guanidinylation | l